# Mobile Performance and Native Boundary Rules

## Goal
Keep the app snappy at startup and prevent slow, gradual performance regression.
Prefer TypeScript by default.
Use Kotlin only when it provides a clear and measurable benefit.

## Core principles
- First screen render is sacred. Protect it.
- Do not add work to startup unless the first visible screen truly depends on it.
- Prefer simple architecture over premature optimization.
- Prefer measurable wins over theoretical purity.
- Do not move logic to Kotlin just because it feels more native.

## Default approach
- Implement new logic in TypeScript first.
- Keep UI logic, app flow, and business rules in TypeScript unless there is a strong reason not to.
- Keep the app root, top-level providers, and bootstrap flow as light as possible.
- Prefer cached or last-known state for first render, then refresh in the background.

## Use Kotlin only when at least one of these is true
- The feature depends on Android platform APIs or system services.
- The feature uses Storage Access Framework or other Android-specific file APIs.
- The task performs heavy file-system access, scans, or indexing.
- The task processes large numbers of files or large payloads.
- The task must run reliably in the background on Android.
- The task involves media playback, audio session integration, or other native media concerns.
- The task is on a performance-critical path and TypeScript is measurably too slow.

## Do not use Kotlin when
- The logic is mostly UI state, app flow, or business rules.
- The problem has not been measured.
- The expected gain is unclear, small, or speculative.
- The complexity cost is likely higher than the performance gain.
- The work can be deferred until after first render.
- The real problem is doing too much work rather than doing it in TypeScript.

## Before proposing Kotlin, first consider
- deferring the work
- caching the result
- doing less work
- reducing frequency
- limiting the data set
- moving the work off the startup path
- loading the feature lazily
- using a simpler TypeScript implementation

## Startup rules
- Do not block first render with non-essential work.
- Defer non-essential file scans, feed refreshes, markdown parsing, artwork loading, and indexing until after first render.
- Lazy-initialize audio unless immediate playback restore is required.
- Do not scan the full vault on startup unless the first visible screen truly depends on fresh scan results.
- Do not parse large markdown sets on startup unless strictly necessary for the initial screen.
- Do not hydrate all stores or initialize all services by default at app launch.
- Avoid one global bootstrap step that eagerly initializes many unrelated systems.

## State and provider rules
- Keep App root and top-level providers minimal.
- Only initialize what the first screen needs.
- Avoid broad global hydration at startup.
- Prefer feature-level initialization over app-wide eager initialization.
- Be cautious with import-time side effects.

## Dependency rules
- Avoid heavy dependencies for small problems.
- Prefer focused libraries over broad utility bundles.
- Be cautious with libraries that perform work at import time.
- Any new dependency must be justified in one sentence.
- Any dependency added to the startup path must be treated as high scrutiny.

## Performance measurement rules
Do not rely on intuition for startup-sensitive changes.
Measure before and after when changing startup behavior or moving logic across the TypeScript and Kotlin boundary.

## Measure when changing
- app startup flow
- root providers
- store hydration
- file scanning
- markdown parsing
- audio initialization
- persistent cache restore
- native module initialization
- dependency loading on the startup path

## Minimum measurement requirement
For startup-sensitive changes, add or update simple timing logs for:
- app process start
- React root mounted
- first screen rendered
- first screen interactive
- file index start and end
- audio init start and end

## Change review requirement
When proposing any of the following:
- new dependency
- new provider
- new startup initialization
- new background process
- new native module
- new persistent cache
- new file scan or parser
- moving logic from TypeScript to Kotlin

Always state:
1. Why this is needed
2. Whether it is on the startup path
3. Whether it can be deferred
4. Why TypeScript is enough or why Kotlin is justified
5. What performance risk this introduces
6. How it should be measured

## Bias for this app
- Full file indexing may use Kotlin because it scans many file names and is performance-sensitive.
- Keep full file indexing off the critical startup path unless the first screen truly depends on fresh results.
- Keep audio playback native where platform integration matters.
- Keep general app flow, UI state, and non-critical business logic in TypeScript.
- If a change risks gradual startup regression, prefer the simpler and more deferrable design.

## Guardrail
If a proposed change makes startup behavior less clear, more eager, or harder to measure, prefer a simpler design.